statement.p:
A commutative ring is tuple (\Lambda,+,\cdot,-,0,1)
consisting of
a set \Lambda, two binary operations + and \cdot
of type \Lambda\times\Lambda\to\Lambda,
a unary operation - : \Lambda\to\Lambda, and two
constants 0,1\in\Lambda,
satisfying the following laws, for all \lambda,\mu,\nu\in\Lambda:


    (\lambda + \mu) + \nu &= \lambda + (\mu + \nu)
    &&\color{blue}\text{(a1)}


    \lambda + 0 &= \lambda
    &&\color{blue}\text{(a2)}


    \lambda + \mu &= \mu + \lambda
    &&\color{blue}\text{(a3)}


    \lambda + (-\lambda) &= 0
    &&\color{blue}\text{(a4)}


    (\lambda\mu)\nu &= \lambda(\mu\nu)
    &&\color{blue}\text{(m1)}


    \lambda 1 &= \lambda
    &&\color{blue}\text{(m2)}


    \lambda\mu &= \mu\lambda
    &&\color{blue}\text{(m3)}


    \lambda(\mu+\nu) &= \lambda\mu + \lambda\nu
    &&\color{blue}\text{(am)}

A field is a commutative ring in which every nonzero element
\lambda has an inverse, i.e., an element \lambda^{-1}
satisfying \lambda \lambda^{-1} = \lambda^{-1}\lambda = 1.

A vector space over the field \Lambda
      is a tuple (V,+,\cdot,-,0)
      consisting of
      a set V, binary operations + : V \times V \to V
      and \cdot : \Lambda \times V \to V,
      a unary operation - : V\to V, and a
      constant 0\in V,
      satisfying the following laws, for all x,y,z\in V
      and \lambda,\mu\in\Lambda:


          (x + y) + z &= x + (y + z)
          &&\color{blue}\text{(a1)}


          x + 0 &= x
          &&\color{blue}\text{(a2)}


          x + y &= y + x
          &&\color{blue}\text{(a3)}


          x + (-x) &= 0
          &&\color{blue}\text{(a4)}


          (\lambda\mu)x &= \lambda(\mu x)
          &&\color{blue}\text{(v1)}


          \lambda (x+y) &= \lambda x + \lambda y
          &&\color{blue}\text{(v2)}


          (\lambda + \mu)x &= \lambda x + \mu x
          &&\color{blue}\text{(v3)}


          1x &= x
          &&\color{blue}\text{(v4)}
